<DIV1 TYPE="title page">
<PB REF="048579_0002_102593FFB0A118C0">
<P>THE MISFORTUNES OF ANGER. A DRAMA, IN TWO PARTS.</P>
<Q><L>"Our Pardons gone, and <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 span"></L>
<L>"We wonder at the Mi&s;chief we have done."</L>
<BIBL>WALLER.</BIBL></Q>
<P><HI>BOSTON.</HI> PRINTED FOR WILLIAM SPOTSWOOD. 1798.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="dramatis personae">
<PB REF="048579_0003_10259406DF68D138">
<HEAD>CHARACTERS.</HEAD>
<LIST>
<ITEM>Mrs. Selwyn, Governe&s;s to Juliet.</ITEM>
<ITEM>Paulina, Her Cou&s;in.</ITEM>
<ITEM>Mary, Her Maid.</ITEM>
<ITEM>Juliet,</ITEM>
<ITEM>Fanny A little Girl.</ITEM>
</LIST>
</DIV1>
</FRONT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="048579_0004_102594086E4C3BE0">
<HEAD>THE Misfortunes of Anger.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>SCENE, a Parlour.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Mary enters, lifts up a tambour frame which appears to have been thrown down, picks up the &s;pan|gles, &s;ilks, &amp;c,&mdash;She &s;peaks.</STAGE>
<P>SO Mi&s;s Juliet has been here, I &s;ee!&mdash;What put her into a rage with her tambour, I wonder?&mdash;Oh! I &s;ee, this ro&s;e-bud does not look well, &s;o down it went, I'll warrant it, and here lie the &s;pan|gles and twi&s;t thrown all over the floor. For my part, I wonder the
<PB N="4" REF="048579_0005_1025940CCDC89C38">
frame was not all broke to &s;ma&s;h, it would have been like her.&mdash;Ah! here comes Mi&s;s Paulina! There's a young lady, marry, I wi&s;h our's was like her, but no hope of that!</P>
<STAGE>Enter Paulina (with a book.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mary have you &s;een my cou&s;in?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Mi&s;s, not &s;ince breakfa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I left her here at her tambour frame&mdash;She &s;aid &s;he would work while I read to her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, Mi&s;s, but &s;ome|thing has gone wrong &s;ince that.&mdash;Here I found the frame, and there lay the &s;ilks&mdash;Truly, I'm glad I was not here, they'd have been thrown at my head.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps &s;he is gone to her own room, I'll &s;eek her; if &s;he comes there in the mean time, Mary tell her I am up &s;tairs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="5" REF="048579_0006_1025940EB2669680">
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Mi&s;s, to be &s;ure I will.&mdash; <STAGE>(<HI>Paulina goes out.</HI>)</STAGE>&mdash;Ah! by my truth, there's &s;ome plea&s;ure in doing any thing for you, one does not get pinched and called names!&mdash;So here's the Governe&s;s, yawning as u&s;ual, but ju&s;t up.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mrs. Selwyn.</HI> (<HI>She &s;peaks in a &s;low, dull manner, and yawns often.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Mary!&mdash;Where's Mi&s;s Juliet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know, Ma'am, not I, &s;he is in one of her pa&s;&s;ions to-day; every thing goes wrong with her; &s;he was ready to fight with the looking-gla&s;s, while I dre&s;&s;ed her this morning, and I don't know how many pinches I got for not being quick enough to plea&s;e her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>She's a &s;trange
<PB N="6" REF="048579_0007_10259411A7B18B78">
girl, I can't help laughing at her &s;ometimes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary. (laughing.)</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis no laugh|ing matter, ma'am, I can tell you that, and it only makes her wor&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>She fatigues me &s;o! I really cannot &s;tay with her long at a time,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary, (a&s;ide.)</SPEAKER>
<P>No, truly, you take care not to have too much trouble!</P>
</SP>
<P><HI>Mrs. Selwyn draws a chair indo|lently, and takes out her work</HI></P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Mary, go and tell her to come to me, I want her to read.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, ma'am I'm quite afraid to go, &s;he won't mind me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn, (yawning.)</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;he'll fatigue me &s;adly too, well, never mind, &s;he'll come bye|and bye.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="7" REF="048579_0008_1025941607251DE8">
<HI>Enter Fanny, (crying)</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's the matter with you, Fanny, what are you crying for?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fanny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Juliet!&mdash;Mi&s;s Juliet!&mdash;Oh dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Child, don't make &s;o much noi&s;e, what has Mi&s;s Juliet done to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fanny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, ma'am, an plea&s;e you &s;he met me in the garden, a|bout half an hour agone, I was a coming up, ma'am, to beg a little milk for my little &s;i&s;ter, for mo|ther is very bad, and &s;o &s;he &s;aid as how&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't talk &s;o fa&s;t, let's hear what Mi&s;s Juliet did.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fanny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, ma'am, and &s;o ma'am, if you plea&s;e, I met Mi&s;s Juliet; and &s;o &s;he a&s;ked me what I wanted, and &s;o I told, and &s;o the</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="048579_0009_10259417EB186CC8">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Grant me pa|tience! How many more <HI>&s;o's?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't make &s;uch a long &s;tory, Fanny, tell us, at once, what made you cry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fanny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I'm a going, &s;o mi&s;s a&s;ked me to play wi' &s;he, for &s;he &s;aid his honour was gone out and Madam Selwyn wa'nt up, and Ma&s;ter Charles was gone to &s;chool, and Mi&s;s Paulina was up &s;tairs, and &s;he did not know what to do wi' her&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, there's all the family di&s;po&s;ed of.&mdash;Well, child, what then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fanny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then we went up &s;tairs ma'am, and mi&s;s &s;hewed me her doll, and we played, but at la&s;t,&mdash;Oh dear, oh dear!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never heard &s;uch a girl in my life.&mdash;What happened then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="9" REF="048579_0010_1025941B39B623B0">
<SPEAKER>Fanny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, mi&s;s beat me, yes, &s;he did, ever &s;o hard, and &s;cratch'd me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, all at once, without any cau&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fanny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, ma'am, cau&s;e I let the doll fall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn,</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(laughing.)</STAGE>
<P>What non&s;en&s;e!&mdash;Go away, child, take your milk, and bid the cook give you &s;ome broth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Fanny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, ma'am, thank you ma'am <STAGE>(Aside.)</STAGE>&mdash;But I wo'nt come here any more to be beat a|bout &s;o. <STAGE>(Mary and Fanny go out.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Juliet, (with her doll.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where's Fanny Wood?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gone home, mi&s;s, do you think any body will &s;tay where you are, to be beat and &s;cratched?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't care What
<PB N="10" REF="048579_0011_1025941FB1C614A8">
bu&s;ine&s;s had &s;he to throw down my doll?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you think &s;he did it on purpo&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know.&mdash;Let her take more care then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has &s;he &s;poil'd it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>No.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well then, what was there to be in &s;uch a rage a|bout?&mdash;Come and read.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not till I have dre&s;&s;ed my doll.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well,&mdash;make ha&s;te then&mdash; <STAGE>(A pau&s;e, Mrs. Selwyn works but &s;lowly and idly, Juliet dre&s;&s;es her doll, at la&s;t, &s;he &s;tamps her foot, and &s;ays:</STAGE>&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<P>You tire&s;ome creature, won't you be dre&s;s'd?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;tars, Mi&s;s Juliet, how you make one &s;tart&mdash;What is the matter now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="048579_0012_1025A1919CB4F020">
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my na&s;ty doll is &s;uch a torment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very pretty, to quarrel with a bit of painted wood!&mdash;Oh! you &s;illy child!&mdash;Come, leave your doll, and let me hear you read.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you I won't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! you are a &s;weet little girl, &s;o mild and &s;o ob|liging; how every body loves you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet, (Crying.)</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me alone then!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pretty creature!&mdash;What a &s;weet face!&mdash;Look how your doll &s;tares at you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>(Ri&s;ing in a pa&s;&s;ion, and throwing her doll acro&s;s the room.)</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<P>I wi&s;h the doll was a thou&s;and miles off, a little provoking crea|ture!&mdash; <STAGE>(Mrs. Selwyn laughs.)</STAGE>&mdash;I won't be laugh'd at that I won't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>How will you
<PB N="12" REF="048579_0013_1025A19439942878">
help it?&mdash;Leave off crying direct|ly, or I will &s;hut you up for two hours.&mdash; <STAGE>(Another pau&s;e, Juliet &s;till cries, but by degrees becomes quiet, af|ter &s;ome time &s;he calls.)</STAGE>&mdash;Mary!&mdash;Mary</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>What now, mi&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I want Mary.&mdash; <STAGE>(calls)</STAGE>&mdash;Mary, I &s;ay!</P>
<STAGE>Enter Mary.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy, mi&s;s I came as &s;oon as ever I heard you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are always &s;o &s;low.&mdash;Take down my gold finch, and fetch me &s;ome feed and water.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes mi&s;s. <STAGE>(She reaches the bird down, then goes out, and returns with &s;ome water and &s;eed.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come my pretty, let your mi&s;tre&s;s feed you, I love you very much&mdash; <STAGE>(She feeds it.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="048579_0014_1025A199086C5388">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, you love it va&s;tly ju&s;t now, but &s;ometimes you are ready to wring its neck, when it does not eat to please you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary. (a&s;ide.)</SPEAKER>
<P>One would think Mrs. Selwyn liked to &s;ee her in a pa&s;&s;ion, &s;he delights &s;o in teaz|ing her!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.(feeding the bird)</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, you little torment you won't eat out of my hand!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, I told you &s;o, now, mi&s;s, you has better beat the bird, or throw it acro&s;s the room, as you did your doll.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>So I will, if I please.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do, I would ad|vi&s;e you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear ma'am, how can you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, eat then&mdash;You <HI>won't!</HI>&mdash;You na&s;ty, little ob&s;ti|nate, ungrateful creature,&mdash;I'll
<PB N="14" REF="048579_0015_1025A19A95A601E8">
teach you to teaze me, I will.&mdash; <STAGE>(She &s;natches the bird out of the cage in a pa&s;&s;ion, gives it a &s;queeze, then looks at it, and bur&s;ts into tears.)</STAGE>&mdash;Oh! Heaven, I have killed my bird!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, dear, mi&s;s, I hope not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look at it, Mary, pray try if you can fetch it to life!&mdash;Oh my poor bird&mdash;Is it dead, Mary?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, mi&s;s, you have killed it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>It&mdash;<HI>I have killed it!</HI>&mdash;I that loved it &s;o!&mdash;Oh! how un|happy I am!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't cry &s;o, mi&s;s, you was not &s;o much to blame now.</P>
<STAGE>Enter Paulina</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Juliet, what's the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="048579_0016_1025A19D21328900">
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(<HI>Throws her&s;elf into Paulina's arms.</HI>)</STAGE>
<P>Oh! cou&s;in, why did you leave me?&mdash;I am never &s;o naughty when you are with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear, I have been &s;eeking you, at la&s;t I heard you was playing with Fanny Wood, &s;o then I &s;at down to write to mama&mdash;But what has happened?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Mi&s;s Juliet has been in one of her u&s;ual furies.&mdash;I mu&s;t dre&s;s.&mdash;I am tired out with her.&mdash;Mary will tell you, Mi&s;s Paulina. <STAGE>(She goes out.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary, (muttering.)</SPEAKER>
<P>And 'tis as much your fault as her's this time, I mu&s;t &s;ay, teaze, teaze, for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mary, what is the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I tell, mi&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! my cou&s;in will hate me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="16" REF="048579_0017_1025A19F87A77CE8">
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hate you, my dear, no I &s;hall pity you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, mi&s;s, my young lady was feeding her bird, and hurt it &s;omehow, and 'tis dead.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Paulina, that is not all; I was angry with my poor bird, I gave it a &s;udden &s;queeze, and killed it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear cou&s;in, you almo&s;t redeem your faults by this openne&s;s of heart.&mdash;How I pity you, how much you mu&s;t feel on this occa&s;ion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(<HI>weeping, but with gen|tlene&s;s.</HI>)</STAGE> But you, who are &s;o good, how much you mu&s;t dete&s;t me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>To tell you the truth, Mi&s;s Paulina, my young lady was not &s;o much to blame as &s;he is &s;ometimes, Mrs. Selwyn did teaze her &s;adly, that &s;he did, to be &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>But that was not my
<PB N="17" REF="048579_0018_1025A1A2E1BC8D08">
bird's fault!&mdash;Ah, my poor bird, he will never eat out of my hand again!&mdash;How could I be &s;o cruel as to hurt a little creature who loved me &s;o dearly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Leave us, Mary.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Mary goes out.)</STAGE>
<STAGE>Paulina, Juliet.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not di&s;tre&s;s your|&s;elf &s;o much, my dear Juliet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do I not de&s;erve to be di&s;tre&s;&s;ed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have certainly been wrong.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! You do not know half how naughty I have been: I pinched Mary, I beat Fanny Wood!&mdash;What is it makes me &s;o wicked, Paulina? I always know when I am &s;o, and I am unhappy, then I fret, and do wrong again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can ea&s;ily conceive
<PB N="18" REF="048579_0019_1025A1A5FB1A37F0">
all that, you are greatly to be piti|ed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you are the only per&s;on (except my father) who e|ver &s;peaks to me as if I had com|mon &s;en&s;e!&mdash;Mary &s;hrugs up her &s;houlders and leaves me as &s;oon as &s;he can.&mdash;Mrs. Selwyn laughs at me and treats me like a baby. It was but ju&s;t now &s;he bade me <HI>"look how my doll &s;tared at me!"</HI> And that put me into &s;uch a pa&s;|&s;ion, that I threw my doll acro&s;s the room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly Mrs. Sel|wyn does not treat you properly, but that does not ju&s;tify you. You are now, my dear, more than twelve years old; at that age, though children, we are no longer babies, but you do not &s;eek to improve your&s;elf. You read, indeed, be|cau&s;e you love reading, but not
<PB N="19" REF="048579_0020_1025A1A9A84F03F8">
with a &s;teady view to your own improvement, and almo&s;t all the remainder of your time is &s;pent in dre&s;&s;ing your doll and playing with Fanny Wood, who is too ignorant to be a proper companion for you; thus you tempt others to treat you like a baby.&mdash;I do not offend you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no,&mdash;I like to hear you because you &s;peak to me gently, and I feel what you &s;ay. Pray, dear Paulina, tell me what I mu&s;t do to be like you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Juliet, I wi&s;h you a better example;&mdash;if you were with us, mama would &s;oon teach you to be all your friends could wi&s;h.&mdash;But Juliet, with the under&s;tanding nature has given you, you may do much for your&s;elf. In the words of a very great author I will tell you that
<Q><PB N="20" REF="048579_0021_1025A1ABF67669D0">
<L>&mdash;"There is no &s;oul</L>
<L>More able to direct you than your&s;elf.</L>
<L>If with the &s;ap of Rea&s;on you would quench</L>
<L>Or but allay the Fire of Pa&s;&s;ion!"&mdash;</L></Q></P>
<P>Read more, and reflect&mdash;When|ever you find your&s;elf getting an|gry leave the cau&s;e of your di&s;|plea&s;ure, take a book which amu|&s;es you, and read till you find your|&s;elf calm and ea&s;y. Struggle with your violent pa&s;&s;ions, and think to what dreadful con&s;equences they will lead if you indulge them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;equences!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my dear cou&s;in, I know not to what an exce&s;s they may tran&s;port you in time, if they are not now oppo&s;ed.&mdash;My mother told me, the other day, &s;he had ju&s;t read the hi&s;tory of a man, who, when a boy, &s;queezed his &s;quirrel to death
<PB N="21" REF="048579_0022_1025A1AE4EE90828">
as you did your bird, and when he grew up, after various crimes, be|ing angry with his wife, his child, who was in her arms, happened to cry while he was &s;peaking and, in a fit of pa&s;&s;ion, he laid his hand on it, and &s;trangled it in a moment!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Heaven, how &s;hocking; do you think it <HI>po&s;&s;ible,</HI> Paulina, do you think it <HI>po&s;&s;ible</HI> I &s;hould ever do &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is impo&s;&s;ible to &s;ay to what extravagance pa&s;&s;ion may lead!&mdash;But ye&s;terday you would have dete&s;ted the idea of injuring your bird&mdash;and are we not told in the Bible, that when the Prophet foretold to Hazael <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">Sec 8th Chapter of the <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 word"> Book of Kings.</NOTE> the mi&s;eries he would bring on his country, and the cruelties of which he would be
<PB N="22" REF="048579_0023_1025A1AFDB8BA6A8">
guilty he exclaimed, "Is thy &s;er|vant a <HI>dog</HI> that he &s;hould do this <HI>great</HI> thing?"&mdash;And yet when he gave way to his pa&s;&s;ions, he exactly ver<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="3 letters"> the Prophet's words.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Paulina! you te|rify me extremely&mdash;I will indeed try to do good&mdash;I will not beat Fanny nor pinch Charles any more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you may not&mdash;It is time for us to dre&s;s, your father will be at home pre&s;ently, and I hear Charles is ju&s;t come from &s;chool. <STAGE> <HI>(They go out.)</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST PART.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="part">
<PB REF="048579_0024_1025A1B261F96B10">
<HEAD>THE Misfortunes of Anger. PART II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Juliet enters from the garden, &s;he draws a chair, &s;its down, and leads her head on her hand.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I HAVE a &s;ad head-ach, it always comes when I cry &s;o much.&mdash;How true is what Paulina &s;aid just now, that I make my&s;elf wretched by indulging my pa&s;&s;ions I&mdash;Why did nobody ever tell me &s;o before?&mdash; <STAGE>(She takes a picture from her bo&s;om and ki&s;&s;es it.</STAGE>&mdash;Oh, my dear mother!&mdash;You died too early to form by your example, the
<PB N="24" REF="048579_0025_1025A1B59C8D9DB8">
daughter you loved &s;o tenderly!&mdash;Wretched girl!&mdash;Why do I ever, for a moment, forget the character which my father drew of my mother when he gave me this picture,&mdash;"Be like your mo|ther, my Juliet; &s;he was mild and gentle to all, &s;he was beloved by every one who knew her! her dy|ing wi&s;h was, that you might be virtuous!&mdash;My child, be worthy of your mother!&mdash;Yes, tho&s;e were exactly his words. Ah! how little do I fulfil her wi&s;hes!&mdash;I, who ill-treat the &s;ervant to who&s;e care &s;he intru&s;ted my infancy&mdash;Who a|bu&s;e a poor child who&s;e &s;ituation &s;hould make me pity her!&mdash;I whom every body hates!&mdash;Torn by contrary feelings!&mdash;Capable of knowing when I do wrong, yet yielding to the next temptation.&mdash;In &s;pite of my faults, am I not to be pitied?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="25" REF="048579_0026_1025A1B8B4331538">
<HI>Enter Mary.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s, my ma&s;ter bade me tell you he is going to Mr. Richley's, and &s;hall be back in le&s;s than an hour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is the matter mi&s;s, you are crying?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have rea&s;on to cry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;ure, mi&s;s, I don't know any young lady who might be happier.&mdash;You have the be&s;t of fathers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! that is true.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>And here you have a fine hou&s;e, where you are, as one may &s;ay, mi&s;tre&s;s, and a carriage, and every earthly thing you can wi&s;h.&mdash;Only think of the poor children down in the village: the little Wood's who&s;e mother is &s;o &s;ick, and who are half &s;tarved!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="048579_0027_1025A1BB39CC5B30">
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas, yes!&mdash;And I have ill-treated poor Fanny!&mdash;My dear Mary, do go down to the village and give her this &s;hilling; I will beg papa, pre&s;ently, to &s;end our a|pothecary to her mother,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, mi&s;s, what a pity you are not always good, how eve|ry body would love you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope they will in fu|ture.</P>
<STAGE>Enter Paulina.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Juliet, what are you going to do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am going to read to Mrs. Selwyn, in her own room, and afterwards Charles and I are going to play.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, then I will fini&s;h my letter to mama.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do &s;o.&mdash;I &s;hall not stay long with Mrs. Selwyn.&mdash;Let
<PB N="27" REF="048579_0028_1025A1BDCEC017B0">
me know, Mary, when my father comes in.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, mi&s;s. <STAGE>(Ju|liet goes out.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Paulina, Mary.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Juliet &s;eems very unhappy to-day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;he has naturally a &s;trong &s;en&s;e of what is right; &s;he feels that &s;he is wrong, and of cour&s;e is unhappy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot help loving her, though &s;he is &s;ometimes &s;o much out of the way. She was a &s;weet child before &s;he grew &s;o pa&s;&s;ionate, and &s;he has a great deal of good about her &s;till. How my poor lady would have grieved had &s;he lived to &s;ee her &s;o head-&s;trong.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Had it plea&s;ed Hea|ven to &s;pare Mrs. Beecher, Juliet would probably have been a very
<PB N="28" REF="048579_0029_1025A1C075526BD0">
different character; &s;he has an ad|mirable under&s;tanding, but &s;he is ill educated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's true, indeed, mi&s;s. I take the liberty of &s;peak|ing to you becau&s;e you know how I love all this family, and that I have lived in it long enough to know &s;omething about it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Mary, you may &s;peak to me without fear; I know your attachment to your late lady and all that belonged to her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, mi&s;s, I wi&s;h my young lady lived with you, you are &s;o mild and &s;o &s;en&s;ible, and my lady your mother is &s;o fine a char|acter&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have rea&s;on to glo|ry in my mother&mdash;May I be one day like her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>You will, mi&s;s, nay, you <HI>are</HI> already; truly I hear of you
<PB N="29" REF="048579_0030_1025A1C2C67434D8">
from all parts.&mdash;But I know yo don't wi&s;h to be prai&s;ed.&mdash;What I was going to &s;ay, is this:&mdash;Nobo|dy hears us!&mdash;No&mdash;Indeed, Mi&s;s Paulina, Mrs. Selwyn is not fit to have the care of my young lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is true indeed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>She &s;ets her no example but lazine&s;s, and &s;he teazes her out of her wits;&mdash;if you had but heard her this morning&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee it with pain. She has no command over my cou|&s;in, becau&s;e &s;he puts her&s;elf on a le|vel with her by mean teazing and raillery;&mdash;a pa&s;&s;ionate temper was never mended by irritation.&mdash;By the way, I don't much like this &s;cheme of playing with Charles; Juliet and he always quarrel, and I am afraid he will overthrow all her good re&s;olutions. I mean to &s;peak to my uncle, to-night, about Mrs.
<PB N="30" REF="048579_0031_1025A1C452857C50">
Selwyn, not to blame or cen&s;ure her, but merely to &s;ay I think &s;he does not exactly follow the right method of managing my cou&s;in's temper.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Truly I think not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I intend to a&s;k my un|cle to let Juliet return with me, I know mama wi&s;hes it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h he may, mi&s;s, with all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I will go and write my letter.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(She is going, when Juliet ru&s;hes in apparently much terrified.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Paulina!&mdash;Mary&mdash;Help, help!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear, mi&s;s what, is the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>My brother!&mdash;help&mdash;help him&mdash;go to him.</P>
<STAGE>(Mary runs out, Juliet &s;inks down with her head again&s;t a chair, Paulina goes to her.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="048579_0032_1025A1C70851A768">
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cou&s;in!&mdash;My dear Juliet, what is the matter?&mdash;Oh, Heaven! &s;he is fainting!&mdash;What &s;hall I do, &s;hall I run to Charles?&mdash;No, I cannot leave this dear girl.&mdash;Juliet, revive, &s;mell to my &s;alts.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Juliet recovering, ri&s;es on her knees, and clings round Pauli|na.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Paulina!&mdash;Send for &s;ome help.&mdash;Run to my father.&mdash;My father!&mdash;Good Heaven! he will hate me for ever.&mdash;I &s;hall be bani&s;hed his &s;ight; plead for me Paulina!&mdash;Wretched girl!&mdash;What will become of me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>For pity's &s;ake tell me what you have done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>What have I done?&mdash;I know not!&mdash;Perhaps I have kill|ed my brother!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(<HI>&s;hudders and &s;hrinks back.</HI>)</STAGE> Unhappy girl!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="32" REF="048579_0033_1025A1CA1C8529A8">
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! well may you &s;hud|der, well may you look at me with horror!&mdash;You who warned me; how dare I cla&s;p my arms round you.&mdash;Tho&s;e hands, which, (how can I five to tell it) perhaps have murdered my brother. <STAGE>(She faints)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>With what terror do I hear her, <STAGE><HI>(She leans over her.)</HI> </STAGE> Wretched victim of ungovern'd pa&s;&s;ion!&mdash;Revive, fear not my re|proaches!&mdash;Ah, thou art already too mi&s;erable!</P>
<STAGE>Enter Mary</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, mi&s;s, what &s;hall we do?&mdash;I have &s;ent for a &s;urgeon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>How is he hurt?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! I know not how much, the knife has &s;truck him near the eye.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>The knife!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, they were at play and quarrelled, Mi&s;s Juliet had a
<PB N="33" REF="048579_0034_1025A1CDEE0330A8">
knife in her hand, which &s;he threw at him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>How dreadful!&mdash;let us run to him!&mdash;Yet, Juliet! But why &s;hould I &s;eek to revive her!&mdash;Unhappy creature, &s;he wakes but to woe&mdash;Perhaps he may be blind|ed!&mdash;I &s;tiffen with horror!&mdash;Ah I hear the &s;urgeon; follow me, Mary!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(They run out.)</HI><HI>(Juliet alone and recovering.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<P>Paulina, where am I!&mdash;You will not &s;peak!&mdash;What have I done!&mdash;Ah I remember&mdash;too, too well I remember!&mdash; <STAGE>(She rai&s;es her|&s;elf)</STAGE>&mdash;They are gone!&mdash;They leave me!&mdash;to die alone!&mdash;Alas I de&s;erve it!&mdash;Am I worthy that one creature &s;hould pity me!&mdash;Yet the torments I endure!&mdash;Can they alone for my crimes?&mdash;Ne|ver, never!&mdash;Dreadful idea!&mdash;mu&s;t I &s;uffer thro' life the angui&s;h I
<PB N="34" REF="048579_0035_1025A1CF7A9325D0">
feel at this moment?&mdash;Thro' life&mdash;what terrible fears crowd upon me!&mdash; <STAGE>(She kneels,)</STAGE> Oh God of mer|cy! hear me, pity me!&mdash;Ah He is a God of <HI>ju&s;tice!</HI>&mdash;Can he for|give <HI>me</HI> who have murdered my Brother?&mdash;What a wretch am I!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mary.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Juliet, are you better?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Mary.&mdash;Have you &s;een&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your brother?&mdash;yes, Mi&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, you weep!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Truly yes, I am fright|ened to death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am the unhappy cau&s;e.&mdash;I dread to hear&mdash;I dare not a&s;k.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;urgeon is with him; I could not &s;tay any longer to &s;ee him &s;uffer &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="35" REF="048579_0036_1025A1D14B388B18">
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suffer!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, the &s;urgeon is o|bliged to hurt him, to find if the wound is&mdash;I cannot &s;peak it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Mortal</HI> you would &s;ay? How is it that I have courage to pronounce that horrible word?&mdash;Ah, I gather courage from the ex|ce&s;s of my de&s;pair.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh my poor ma&s;ter, what will he &s;ay!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not di&s;tract me!&mdash;Pity for a moment the pangs I &s;uffer!&mdash;Leave me, Mary, leave me, I implore you!&mdash;Go, learn if there is any hope!</P>
<STAGE>(Mary goes out.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have lo&s;t every|thing!&mdash;My father will drive me from him for ever&mdash;I &s;hall quit every thing I love!&mdash;My friends, my relations will blu&s;h when my name is mentioned&mdash;Never more
<PB N="36" REF="048579_0037_1025A1D459778418">
&s;hall I revi&s;it the&s;e &s;cenes, &s;o dear to my infancy!&mdash;Let me not re|call the years I have pa&s;t&mdash;years of innocence and happine&s;s!&mdash;Go where I will, I &s;hall be pointed at and hated.&mdash;Even the picture of my mother, which u&s;ed in all my di&s;tre&s;&s;es to con&s;ole me, I can never fee again.&mdash;I &s;hould fancy it re|proached me.&mdash;And all this mi&s;e|ry I have incurred by one moment of pa&s;&s;ion!&mdash;Oh God, if thou &s;hould'&s;t this once deign to &s;ave me, never, never, will I be guilty again!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Paulina, (running.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Juliet!&mdash;my dear cou&s;in!&mdash;be comforted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! what then!&mdash;What!&mdash;may I, dare I hope!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;the &s;urgeon &s;ays he is in no danger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(throwing her&s;elf into her arms.)</STAGE> Oh my be&s;t Paulina!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="37" REF="048579_0038_1025A1D6A4F22140">
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(embracing her with tears.)</STAGE> I ran to you the in&s;tant I heard it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have not de&s;erved your goodne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah Juliet!&mdash;if the knife had gone ever &s;o little on one &s;ide, Charles would have been kil|led, or on the other, and he would have been blinded for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh merciful Almighty God!&mdash;from what mi&s;ery has thy providence pre&s;erved me!&mdash;even now I cannot behold my&s;elf with|out horror.&mdash;Have I de&s;erved the mercy I have met with?&mdash;No!&mdash;tho' innocent in intention, my action was guilty&mdash;I could not wi&s;h to hurt my brother, yet took the means to do &s;o!&mdash;Dete&s;ted pa&s;&s;ion!&mdash;Oh Paulina, I am cured for ever!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I dare hope &s;o!&mdash;
<PB N="38" REF="048579_0039_1025A1D83315D1E0">
The le&s;&s;ons of this day have been &s;triking.&mdash;They &s;hew how one &s;tep in evil leads to another.&mdash;Aweful and horrid might have been the e|vent, but as it has proved, we will hope this in&s;truction has been di|rected by Providence, to warn you of your danger!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>It has done it com|pletely.&mdash;But Paulina, where is my father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hear him now in the hall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Paulina, I dare not &s;ee him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will go to him, and I hope, return with your pardon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>My be&s;t friend&mdash;let actions &s;peak my gratitude, deign but to coun&s;el and direct me, henceforth I will be guided by you alone.</P>
<STAGE>(Paulina goes out)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="39" REF="048579_0040_1025A1DB9C695C78">
<HI>Enter Mrs. Selwyn and Mary.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Mi&s;s Juliet, make your&s;elf ea&s;y, all goes well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank God!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have had good fortune, Mi&s;s, I can tell you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good fortune, Ma'am! I dare to con&s;ider it as the act of Divine Providence, if not to &s;ave <HI>me,</HI> yet to pre&s;erve my father from mi&s;ery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>You improve, Mi&s;s, your language is really fine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Misfortunes correct the heart, and &s;trong feelings excite &s;trong expre&s;&s;ion.&mdash;I hope I &s;hall improve.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>You a&s;toni&s;h me&mdash;you who but this morning were dre&s;&s;ing your doll, to be making wi&s;e remarks, is indeed &s;urpri&s;ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am not a fool, tho' I have acted like one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, they an't very
<PB N="40" REF="048579_0041_10258E89E3351B78">
wi&s;e that take you for a fool. I have often heard you talk to my ma&s;ter as &s;en&s;ible as any-body in the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Juliet ne|ver indulged me with any of her &s;en&s;ible conver&s;ation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>Truly no, becau&s;e you treated her like a baby.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>You take great liberties.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mary.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg your pardon, Ma'am, but I have often told you you did not know my young lady &s;o well as I did.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Selwyn.</SPEAKER>
<P>The more &s;en&s;e &s;he has, the more &s;hame for her to behave as &s;he has done.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Too true indeed!&mdash;my con&s;cience tells me I have not the excu&s;e of folly.&mdash;But I have &s;uf|fered pa&s;&s;ion to over-run and darken many good qualities. This one
<PB N="41" REF="048579_0042_1025A1E16035B270">
hour has driven it from my heart. I am no longer a fooli&s;h child.</P>
<STAGE>Enter Paulina.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, my deare&s;t Juliet&mdash;Charles is with your fa|ther, he knows all, he forgives you, he calls for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>I owe every-thing to you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have more good news for you&mdash;one word.</P>
<STAGE>(Mrs. Selwyn and Mary retire to the back of the Scene.)</STAGE>
<P>You go home with me&mdash;you are to &s;tay with us as long as you plea&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Delightful!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your father di&s;mi&s;&s;es Mrs. Selwyn.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah I am &s;orry! She is poor, and &s;he has taught the ma|ny things.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>My good cou&s;in, how
<PB N="42" REF="048579_0043_1025A1E2EC47EC18">
I love that gratitude!&mdash;your fa|ther will allow her a pen&s;ion, we have &s;ettled all that &s;ince I left you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh my be&s;t cou&s;in!&mdash;how much do I owe you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am overpaid if you are happy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Juliet.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;o I mu&s;t be good.&mdash;That will be the work of your hands!&mdash;How will you be loved by your friends, by your mother, by Heaven it&s;elf!&mdash;yes that <HI>will</HI> repay you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Paulina.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let us go, my uncle expects us.</P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>Scene clo&s;es.</TRAILER>
